{"award_age":41.0,"bio_image":"full\/cbe68a2a6948e1af146d69a77ed1a70ece84d757.jpg","category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1918-03-03T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"2007-10-26T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/a\/ad\/Arthur_Kornberg.jpg\/220px-Arthur_Kornberg.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Arthur_Kornberg","mini_bio":"<p><b>Arthur Kornberg<\/b> (March 3, 1918 \u2013 October 26, 2007) was an <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States\" title=\"United States\">American<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Biochemist\" title=\"Biochemist\">biochemist<\/a> who won the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine\">Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine<\/a> 1959 for his discovery of \"the mechanisms in the biological synthesis of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Deoxyribonucleic_acid\" title=\"Deoxyribonucleic acid\" class=\"mw-redirect\">deoxyribonucleic acid<\/a> (DNA)\" together with Dr. <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Severo_Ochoa\" title=\"Severo Ochoa\">Severo Ochoa<\/a> of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/New_York_University\" title=\"New York University\">New York University<\/a>. He was also awarded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Paul-Lewis_Award_in_Enzyme_Chemistry\" title=\"Paul-Lewis Award in Enzyme Chemistry\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Paul-Lewis Award in Enzyme Chemistry<\/a> from the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/American_Chemical_Society\" title=\"American Chemical Society\">American Chemical Society<\/a> in 1951, L.H.D. degree from <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Yeshiva_University\" title=\"Yeshiva University\">Yeshiva University<\/a> in 1962, as well as <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/National_Medal_of_Science\" title=\"National Medal of Science\">National Medal of Science<\/a> in 1979.<\/p><p>His primary research interests were in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Biochemistry\" title=\"Biochemistry\">biochemistry<\/a>, especially <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Enzyme\" title=\"Enzyme\">enzyme<\/a> chemistry, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Deoxyribonucleic_acid\" title=\"Deoxyribonucleic acid\" class=\"mw-redirect\">deoxyribonucleic acid<\/a> synthesis (<a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/DNA_replication\" title=\"DNA replication\">DNA replication<\/a>) and studying the nucleic acids which control heredity in animals, plants, bacteria and viruses.<sup id=\"cite_ref-frs_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Arthur_Kornberg#cite_note-frs-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"Arthur Kornberg","place_of_birth":"New York City ,  United States","place_of_death":"Stanford ,  United States","text":"Arthur Kornberg , Physiology or Medicine, 1959","year":1959.0}